         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">15/12/67 ¶  ¶ I was very glad, dear Prof. Anderson, to receive from the Linnean Society lately your excellent memoir of the Asiatic Acanthaceae. ¶  With the aid of this exquisite essay I shall be able...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">67.12.15</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Thomas Anderson</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh, Thomas Anderson, box 2, letters from various originators 1859-68, vol. 1, no. 171 cont.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The guard paper on to which the MS is pasted is numbered '171 contd.' with an arrow pointing to the front of the folio. It is followed by an undated fragment, numbered '171' on its guard paper. That folio is given here as the first two paragraphs of the postscript.</p>
               </note>15/12/67</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was very glad, dear Prof. Anderson, to receive from the Linnean Society lately your excellent memoir of the Asiatic <name key="Acanthaceae">Acanthaceae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Anderson (1867).</p>
               </note> With the aid of this exquisite essay I shall be able to fix the position of the few Austral. <name key="Acanthaceae">Acanthaceae</name>, not above a dozen!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>My garden is dreadfully poor in this showy plant. I have not even <name key="Graptophyllum">Graptophyllum</name> in cultivation.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Should you, as I hope, work on American <name key="Acanthaceae">Acanthaceae</name> I will gladly send you all mine. I have some from Moritzi and others not even contained in the Kew collection.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/> Do you find difficulty in raising <name key="Acanthaceae">Acanthaceae</name> from seeds?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am greatly obliged for your friendly mediation of my communications with Java.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to T. Anderson, 25 March 1867 and M to T. Anderson, 24 May 1867.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">your very regardful</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Pray give your excellent brother<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Presumably John Anderson.</p>
               </note> my kind regards</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Acclimation Society introduces no carnivorous or ferocious animals, but any thing like deer, gamebirds &amp;c. We keep up no regular menagerie, as our fund not admits of it. I fear I shall never be able to get a specimen of Casuarius Johnsonii for your Museum the bird being so excessively rare. Indeed only a year ago I named it &amp; made it preliminarely known.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B66.12.02. See also M to R. Murchison, 25 December 1866 (in this edition as 66-12-25b).</p>
               </note> Museum-birds I can manage to send, &amp; some other smaller contributions<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M was actively distributing zoological specimens to international museums; see Lucas (2013a). It is not known whether he sent bird specimens to Calcutta.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The remainder of the text is on an un-numbered folio after f. 171. It is placed here on the basis of Anderson (1867), which also confirms the addressee, and of M's 1867 descriptions of <name key="Acanthaceae">Acanthaceae</name> (see n. 8 below).</p>
               </note>Your "<name key="Acanthaceae">Acanthaceae</name>" in the L.S. proceedings have been to me a real boon. I have reduced <name key="Earlia">Earlia</name> to <name key="Graptophyllum">Graptophyllum</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M had erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Earlia">Earlia</name>
                     </seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. excelsa</seg>) in B63.04.01, p. 160, and reduced it to <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Graptophyllum">Graptophyllum</name> earlii</seg> in B67.12.01, p. 87.</p>
               </note> and described 2 new <name key="Dicliptera">Dicliptera</name>s, also 2 or 3 other <name key="Acanthaceae">Acanthaceae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M named <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Dicliptera">Dicliptera</name> armata, D. racemifica, Justicia cavernarum, J. eranthemoides </seg>and<seg style="font-style: italic; "> J. hygrophiloides</seg> in B67.12.01.</p>
               </note> The order is however singularly poor in Australia</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Would the seeds of <name key="Euryale%20ferax">Euryale ferax</name> travel? I have ripened seeds of <name key="Victoria%20regia">Victoria regia</name> in my tank &amp; the plant has been flowering with scarcely any intermission for 11 months<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See Maroske (1992).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have neither <name key="Barclaya">Barclaya</name> &amp;c.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acanthaceae">Acanthaceae</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Barclaya">Barclaya</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Dicliptera">Dicliptera</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Earlia">Earlia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Euryale%20ferax">Euryale ferax</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Graptophyllum">Graptophyllum</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Victoria%20regia">Victoria regia</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
